<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Alberic of Paris</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Oct 28, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Alberic of Paris, also known as Alberic de Monte, was, according to
his contemporaries, one of the most prominent philosophers in Paris in
the twelfth century, a period in which the Latin-speaking West saw a
marked revitalization of philosophical and scientific learning, and in
which Paris rose to become its leading educational center. Alberic was
the main rival to Peter Abelard (1079&ndash;1142) and, in the words of
one of his pupils, &ldquo;a most fierce opponent of the nominalist
school&rdquo;&mdash;that is, of Abelard and his followers (John of
Salisbury, <em>Metalogicon</em>, 2.10). He is best known for having
proved that Abelard&rsquo;s logic was, on its own axioms,
inconsistent.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
	<li><a href="#LifeWork">1. Life and Works</a></li>
	<li><a href="#Meta">2. Metaphysics</a>
