 <a href="#BG2004">Brower and Guilfoy 2004</a>:
 65&ndash;125 (ch. 3). doi:10.1017/CCOL0521772478.004</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, &ldquo;Abelard on Mental
Language&rdquo;, <em>American Catholic Philosophical Quarterly</em>,
81(2): 169&ndash;187. doi:10.5840/acpq200781236</li>

<li>King, Peter and Andrew Arlig, 2018 [2023], &ldquo;Peter
Abelard&rdquo;, in <em>The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</em>
(Fall 2023 edition), Edward N. Zalta and Uri Nodelman (eds), URL =
 &lt;<a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/fall2023/entries/abelard/" target="other">https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/fall2023/entries/abelard/</a>&gt;</li>
 
<li>Lenz, Martin, 2007, &ldquo;Are Thoughts and Sentences
Compositional? A Controversy between Abelard and a Pupil of Alberic on
the Reconciliation of Ancient Theses on Mind and Language&rdquo;,
<em>Vivarium</em>, 45(2): 169&ndash;188.
doi:10.1163/156853407X217704</li>

<li>Lenzen, Wolfgang, 2021, <em>Abaelards Logik</em>, Leiden: Brill.
doi:10.30965/9783969752371</li>

<li>Marenbon, John, 1992, &ldquo;Vocalism, Nominalism and the
Commentaries on the Categories from the Earlier Twelfth
Century&rdquo;, <em>Vivarium</em>, 30(1): 51&ndash;61.
doi:10.1163/156853492X00043</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1993, &ldquo;Medieval Latin Glosses and
Commentaries on Aristotelian Logical Texts, Before c. 1150 AD&rdquo;,
in <em>Glosses and Commentaries on Aristotelian Logical Texts: The
Syriac, Arabic and Medieval Latin Traditions</em> (Warburg Institute
Surveys and Texts 23), Charles Burnett (ed.), London: Warburg
Institute, University of London, 77&ndash;127.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1997, <em>The Philosophy of Peter
Abelard</em>, Cambridge/New York: Cambridge University Press.
doi:10.1017/CBO9780511582714</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013a, <em>Abelard in Four Dimensions: A
Twelfth-Century Philosopher in His Context and Ours</em> (Conway
Lectures in Medieval Studies), Notre Dame, IN: University of Notre
Dame Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013b, &ldquo;The Tradition of Studying the
<em>Categories</em> in the Early Middle Ages (until c. 1200): A
Revised Working Catalogue of Glosses, Commentaries and
Treatises&rdquo;, in <em>Aristotle&rsquo;s Categories in the
Byzantine, Arabic and Latin Traditions</em> (Scientia Danica. Series
H, Humanistica 8, v. 5), Sten Ebbesen, John Marenbon, and Paul Thom
(eds), Copenhagen: Det Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskab,
139&ndash;173 (ch. 5).</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018, &ldquo;The <em>Isagoge</em> in the
Latin Tradition until c.1200&rdquo;, <em>Medioevo</em>, 43:
151&ndash;188.</li>

<li>Marenbon, John and Heine Hansen, 2022, &ldquo;Introduction:
Special Issue on the Twelfth-Century Logical Schools&rdquo;,
<em>Vivarium</em>, 60(2&ndash;3): 113&ndash;136.
doi:10.1163/15685349-06002001</li>

<li>Martin, Christopher J., 1987a, &ldquo;Something Amazing about the
Peripatetic of Pallet: Abaelard&rsquo;s Development of Boethius&rsquo;
Account of Conditional Propositions&rdquo;, <em>Argumentation</em>,
1(4): 419&ndash;436. doi:10.1007/BF00209738</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1987b, &ldquo;Embarrassing Arguments and
Surprising Conclusions in the Development of Theories of the
Conditional in the Twelfth Century&rdquo;, in <em>Gilbert de Poitiers
et ses contemporains: Aux origines de la &ldquo;Logica
modernorum&rdquo;: Actes du septi&egrave;me symposium europ&eacute;en
d&rsquo;histoire de la logique et de la s&eacute;mantique
m&eacute;di&eacute;vales</em> (History of Logic 5), Jean Jolivet and
Alain de Libera (eds), Naples: Bibliopolis, 377&ndash;400.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2004, &ldquo;Logic&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#BG2004">Brower and Guilfoy 2004</a>:
 158&ndash;199 (ch. 5). doi:10.1017/CCOL0521772478.006</li>

<li>Normore, Calvin G., 1987, &ldquo;The Tradition of Medieval
Nominalism&rdquo;, in <em>Studies in Medieval Philosophy</em> (Studies
in Philosophy and the History of Philosophy 17), John F. Wippel (ed.),
Washington, DC: Catholic University of America Press, 201&ndash;217
(ch. 9).</li>

<li>Nuchelmans, Gabri&euml;l, 1973, <em>Theories of the Proposition:
Ancient and Medieval Conceptions of the Bearers of Truth and
Falsity</em> (North-Holland Linguistic Series 8), Amsterdam:
North-Holland.</li>

<li>Panaccio, Claude, 2010, &ldquo;Mental Language and Predication:
Ockham and Abelard&rdquo;, <em>Analytica &ndash; Revista de
Filosofia</em>, 14(2): 183&ndash;193. doi:10.35920/arf.v14i2.603</li>

<li>Parfit, Derek, 1984, <em>Reasons and Persons</em>, Oxford/New
York: Clarendon Press. doi:10.1093/019824908X.001.0001</li>

<li>Pasnau, Robert, 2011, <em>Metaphysical Themes,
1274&ndash;1671</em>, Oxford/New York: Clarendon Press.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199567911.001.0001</li>

<li>Rosier-Catach, Ir&egrave;ne, 2004, &ldquo;Les discussions sur le
signifi&eacute; des propositions chez Ab&eacute;lard et ses
contemporains&rdquo;, in <em>Medieval Theories on Assertive and
Non-Assertive Language</em>, Alfonso Maier&ugrave; and Luisa Valente
(eds), Firenze: Leo S. Olschki, 1&ndash;23.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, &ldquo;Understanding as Attending.
Semantics, Psychology and Ontology in Peter Abelard&rdquo;, in <em>The
Language of Thought in Late Medieval Philosophy: Essays in Honor of
Claude Panaccio</em> (Historical-Analytical Studies on Nature, Mind
and Action 5), Jenny Pelletier and Magali Roques (eds), Cham: Springer
International Publishing, 249&ndash;274.
doi:10.1007/978-3-319-66634-1_16</li>

<li>Schuman, Boaz Faraday, 2024, &ldquo;Do Thoughts Have Parts? Peter
Abelard: <em>Yes!</em> Alberic of Paris: <em>No!</em>&rdquo;,
<em>British Journal for the History of Philosophy</em>, 32(5):
974&ndash;998. doi:10.1080/09608788.2024.2316789</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, forthcoming, &ldquo;Can God&rsquo;s
Knowledge Change? A Characteristic Theo-Logical Doctrine of Alberic
and His School&rdquo; in
 <a href="#HDS2025">Hansen, Donato, and Schumann forthcoming b</a>.</li>
 
<li>Trifogli, Cecilia, 2000, <em>Oxford Physics in the Thirteenth
Century (ca. 1250&ndash;1270): Motion, Infinity, Place, and Time</em>
(Studien und Texte zur Geistesgeschichte des Mittelalters 72),
Leiden/Boston: Brill.</li>

<li>Tweedale, Martin M., 1976, <em>Abailard on Universals</em>,
Amsterdam: North Holland.</li>

<li>Uckelman, Sara L., 2016 [2024], &ldquo;William of Sherwood&rdquo;,
in <em>The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</em> (Winter 2024
edition), Edward N. Zalta and Uri Nodelman (eds). URL =
 &lt;<a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2024/entries/william-sherwood/" target="other">https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2024/entries/william-sherwood/</a>&gt;</li>
 
<li>Wci&oacute;rka, Wojciech, forthcoming, &ldquo;Successive Wholes in
Twelfth-Century Logic: Conceptual Evolution&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#HDS2025">Hansen, Donato, and Schumann forthcoming b</a>.</li>
 
<li>Wilks, Ian, 2008, &ldquo;Peter Abelard and His
Contemporaries&rdquo;, in <em>Mediaeval and Renaissance Logic</em>
(Handbook of the History of Logic 2), Dov M. Gabbay and John Woods
(eds), Amsterdam/New York: Elsevier North Holland, 83&ndash;156.
doi:10.1016/S1874-5857(08)80024-6</li>
</ul>
</div> 

